       \"other\": \"subseafloor or vent-wall redox gradients, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Successive hydrogenation of carbon oxides on iron oxide/metal surfaces generates reduced C1 products including formaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"FTT-like reduction of carbon oxides over magnetite and Fe0 gives reduced organics including aldehydes under hydrothermal conditions; exact product distributions vary, but formaldehyde is a plausible transferable C1 intermediate (McCollom & Seewald, 2007; Cody et al., 2004).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal C-C coupling to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite\", \"pyrite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-430K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline to near-neutral, anoxic, mineral surface concentration\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-assisted reductive carbonyl coupling of C1 species produces a C2 aldehyde-hydroxy compound.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrothermal systems can support reductive homologation and carbonyl coupling from C1 feedstocks; glycolaldehyde is a recognized prebiotic sugar precursor and plausible output from reduced carbon chemistry on iron minerals, though this specific step is partly inferential (Cody et al., 2000; Roldan et al., 2015; speculative connection to complete network).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface borate-stabilized oxidation of glycolaldehyde to glyoxylate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals\", \"TiO2\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed evaporitic pool, borate-rich, anoxic atmosphere\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photocatalytic oxidation and hydration of glycolaldehyde yields glyoxylate while borate suppresses uncontrolled sugar degradation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Surface photochemistry can interconvert small carbonyl compounds, and glyoxylate is frequently invoked as a prebiotic carbonyl hub connected to alpha-keto acid chemistry; borate-rich settings help preserve reactive aldehydes and sugar-like intermediates (Benner et al., 2012; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; speculative but chemically motivated connection).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from CO2 and H2\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite\", \"magnetite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent, Fe2+-rich, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise mineral-catalyzed reduction and C-C bond formation from carbon dioxide affords an alpha-keto acid product.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate is a central alpha-keto acid in origin-of-metabolism models and can arise in iron-sulfur mediated CO2 fixation networks; while yields and exact pathways remain challenging, vent chemistry is frequently invoked as a source of pyruvate-like compounds (Cody et al., 2000; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface cyanide photochemistry to HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2\", \"sulfide minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, evaporative concentration, sulfur-rich setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical and redox transformations of reduced carbon and nitrogen species generate cyanide under strongly reducing, UV-driven surface conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN is a canonical prebiotic hub in surface photochemistry and cyanosulfidic networks; while natural sources include atmospheric and geochemical input, local photochemical generation in sulfide-rich settings is consistent with prebiotic cyanide chemistry (Patel et al., 2015; Xu et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Strecker-type synthesis of alanine from pyruvate precursor pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"sulfide minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling with aminonitrile formation and hydrolysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate-derived carbonyl chemistry with ammonia and cyanide forms aminonitrile-type intermediates that hydrolyze to alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Strecker chemistry is among the best-supported routes to alpha-amino acids in prebiotic environments. Here pyruvate serves as a network-integrating carbonyl source linked to hydrothermal production and surface cyanide chemistry (Miller, 1957; Peltzer et al., 1984; Islam et al., 2003).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite\", \"greigite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic mineral surfaces in vent pores\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Imine formation between pyruvate and ammonia followed by mineral-assisted reduction generates alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids on mineral surfaces is a plausible hydrothermal route to amino acids, directly connecting keto acid hubs to amino acid pools in iron-sulfur settings (Huber & Wachtershauser, 2003; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface HCN oligomerization to adenine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentrating ponds, UV exposure, repeated drying\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Oligomerization of HCN through diaminomaleonitrile-like intermediates culminates in purine ring formation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN oligomerization to adenine is a classic prebiotic route and included here to increase network density around the cyanide hub and connect nitrogen-rich heterocycle chemistry to the same surface feedstock pool (Or\u00f3, 1961; Ferris et al., 1978).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface concentration of cyanamide-like nitrogen chemistry to guanidine/urea pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals\", \"TiO2\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"310-360K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"dry-heating and rehydration cycles in evaporitic pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Concentrated nitrile and ammonia chemistry under dehydration/rehydration yields carbamidine and carbamoyl equivalents including guanidine and urea-like products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Prebiotic nitrile chemistry can furnish activated nitrogen-rich species such as cyanamide, urea, and related carbamidine donors. Guanidine itself is less directly established than urea/cyanamide, so this node represents a necessary but partly speculative condensation pool feeding downstream guanidination chemistry (Lohrmann & Orgel, 1971; Saladino et al., 2007; speculative extension for arginine assembly).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical transamination and homologation from glyoxylate/pyruvate/alanine to ornithine pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentrated prebiotic pools, repeated heating-cooling, mineral interfaces available\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Network-level carbonyl homologation and transamination converts alpha-keto acid and amino acid pools into diamino acid products, with ornithine as the emergent C5 diamino acid node.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Direct prebiotic synthesis of ornithine is not as well established as simple amino acids, but alpha-keto acid/amino acid networks can expand carbon skeleton diversity through aldol-like additions, transamination, and reduction. Ornithine is included as a necessary intermediate for arginine and is therefore a speculative but chemically justified node (Muchowska et al., 2020; Frenkel-Pinter et al., 2021; speculative network-completion step).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical carbamoylation of ornithine to citrulline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"condensing pools with dehydration-rehydration cycles\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic attack of ornithine terminal amino group on carbamoyl donor equivalent yields a ureido side chain.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Citrulline is the immediate carbamoylated precursor to arginine in biology. Prebiotically, urea and related carbamoyl donors can react with amines during drying cycles, making citrulline a plausible intermediate even though direct demonstrations are limited (Lohrmann & Orgel, 1971; Becker et al., 2018; partly speculative connection).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical guanidination of ornithine to arginine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentrated solute phases, mildly alkaline, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Terminal amino group of ornithine attacks a carbamidine/guanidino donor to form the guanidinium side chain of arginine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Guanidination of amines by carbamidine-like donors is chemically plausible and provides the shortest prebiotic route from ornithine to arginine. Direct prebiotic evidence is sparse, so this is a necessary speculative step anchored in known guanidino transfer chemistry and the availability of nitrogen-rich condensation products in cyanide-derived networks (Saladino et al., 2007; Frenkel-Pinter et al., 2021; speculative network-completion step).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical conversion of citrulline to arginine via guanidino enrichment\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"dehydration-rehydration with concentrated carbamidine donors\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Further amidino/guanidino transfer to citrulline-like ureido intermediates yields the fully guanidinated arginine side chain.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Although less direct than ornithine guanidination, citrulline can be viewed as a chemically proximate intermediate toward arginine under nitrogen-rich condensing conditions. This provides an alternate terminal route and reflects uncertainty in exact prebiotic late-stage chemistry (speculative extension justified by network redundancy and biomimetic analogy).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct hydrothermal-to-biochemical ornithine guanidination route\",\n      \"description\": \"CO2 reduction builds pyruvate and alanine hydrothermally, feeding a biochemical ornithine node that is guanidinated to arginine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate with surface cyanide alanine route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate is exported to the surface for Strecker-like alanine synthesis, then converted through ornithine to arginine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate-formaldehyde-glycolaldehyde branch to ornithine\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal C1 fixation produces glycolaldehyde and glyoxylate, which converge with pyruvate/alanine chemistry to form ornithine before guanidination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface guanidine pool with hydrothermal alanine input\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal alanine and surface-derived guanidine are combined through the ornithine hub to reach arginine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Citrulline branch from ornithine\",\n      \"description\": \"Ornithine is first carbamoylated to citrulline, then further converted to arginine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Mixed hydrothermal-surface carbonyl route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde and formate generate glycolaldehyde, which is oxidized to glyoxylate and combined with surface alanine synthesis and guanidination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate-centered dual alanine redundancy route\",\n      \"description\": \"Both hydrothermal reductive amination and surface Strecker chemistry feed the alanine pool, increasing robustness before ornithine formation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN-rich route via guanidine-producing surface chemistry\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface cyanide generation feeds both Strecker amino acid synthesis and guanidine formation, which converge at ornithine to produce arginine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Glyoxylate-assisted carbon skeleton expansion route\",\n      \"description\": \"A hydrothermal-to-surface transfer produces glyoxylate that helps expand carbon skeletons toward ornithine, followed by guanidination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Alternative terminal citrulline-to-arginine route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal and surface chemistry create ornithine and carbamoyl/guanidino donors, with arginine reached through citrulline as terminal intermediate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_014\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Arginine", "overall_strategy": "This network targets arginine by linking hydrothermal carbon fixation and alpha-keto acid generation to surface cyanide and aldehyde chemistry, then using biochemical/prebiotic transamination and guanidination-like assembly to reach ornithine, citrulline, and finally arginine. The network is intentionally convergent around hub intermediates HCN, formaldehyde, pyruvate, glyoxylate, and ornithine, with cross-environment transfer of hydrothermal products into surface Strecker/formose chemistry and subsequent biochemical assembly in concentrated prebiotic pools.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CHOO-", "iupac_name": "methanoate", "common_name": "formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C2H2O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxoacetic acid", "common_name": "glyoxylic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C3H7NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "alanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C3H5NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminoprop-2-enoic acid", "common_name": "dehydroalanine", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "CH5N3", "iupac_name": "guanidine", "common_name": "guanidine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH5N3/c2-1(3)4/h(H5,2,3,4)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "CH4N2O", "iupac_name": "methanamide, amino-oxo-", "common_name": "urea", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH4N2O/c2-1(3)4/h(H4,2,3,4)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C5H11N3O2", "iupac_name": "2,5-diaminopentanoic acid", "common_name": "ornithine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H12N2O2/c6-3-1-2-4(7)5(8)9/h4H,1-3,6-7H2,(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C6H13N3O3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-5-(carbamoylamino)pentanoic acid", "common_name": "citrulline", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H13N3O3/c7-4(6(11)12)2-1-3-9-5(8)10/h4H,1-3,7H2,(H2,8,9,10)(H,11,12)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C6H14N4O2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-5-(diaminomethylideneamino)pentanoic acid", "common_name": "arginine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H14N4O2/c7-4(5(11)12)2-1-3-10-6(8)9/h4H,1-3,7H2,(H,11,12)(H4,8,9,10)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "ethanoic acid", "common_name": "acetic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C6H5N5", "iupac_name": "9H-purin-6-amine", "common_name": "adenine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H5N5/c6-5-4-n3cnc-1-2(4)7-5/h1H,(H4,6,7,8,9,10)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite", "mackinawite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions, anoxic, H2-rich"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface mediated reduction of CO2 by H2 on Fe-S phases to yield surface-bound formyl species that hydrolyze to formate.", "reasoning": "Reduction of CO2 to formate on Fe-S minerals is central to hydrothermal prebiotic carbon fixation and is widely discussed for alkaline vent scenarios; greigite and mackinawite are plausible catalysts and analogs of biological Fe-S clusters (Russell et al., 1994; Cody et al., 2000; Martin et al., 2008)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type generation of formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite", "elemental iron"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subseafloor or vent-wall redox gradients, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Successive hydrogenation of carbon oxides on iron oxide/metal surfaces generates reduced C1 products including formaldehyde.", "reasoning": "FTT-like reduction of carbon oxides over magnetite and Fe0 gives reduced organics including aldehydes under hydrothermal conditions; exact product distributions vary, but formaldehyde is a plausible transferable C1 intermediate (McCollom & Seewald, 2007; Cody et al., 2004)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal C-C coupling to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite", "pyrite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-430K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline to near-neutral, anoxic, mineral surface concentration"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-assisted reductive carbonyl coupling of C1 species produces a C2 aldehyde-hydroxy compound.", "reasoning": "Hydrothermal systems can support reductive homologation and carbonyl coupling from C1 feedstocks; glycolaldehyde is a recognized prebiotic sugar precursor and plausible output from reduced carbon chemistry on iron minerals, though this specific step is partly inferential (Cody et al., 2000; Roldan et al., 2015; speculative connection to complete network)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Surface borate-stabilized oxidation of glycolaldehyde to glyoxylate", "inputs": ["mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals", "TiO2"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed evaporitic pool, borate-rich, anoxic atmosphere"}, "mechanism": "Photocatalytic oxidation and hydration of glycolaldehyde yields glyoxylate while borate suppresses uncontrolled sugar degradation.", "reasoning": "Surface photochemistry can interconvert small carbonyl compounds, and glyoxylate is frequently invoked as a prebiotic carbonyl hub connected to alpha-keto acid chemistry; borate-rich settings help preserve reactive aldehydes and sugar-like intermediates (Benner et al., 2012; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; speculative but chemically motivated connection)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from CO2 and H2", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite", "magnetite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent, Fe2+-rich, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Stepwise mineral-catalyzed reduction and C-C bond formation from carbon dioxide affords an alpha-keto acid product.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate is a central alpha-keto acid in origin-of-metabolism models and can arise in iron-sulfur mediated CO2 fixation networks; while yields and exact pathways remain challenging, vent chemistry is frequently invoked as a source of pyruvate-like compounds (Cody et al., 2000; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Surface cyanide photochemistry to HCN", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2", "sulfide minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation, evaporative concentration, sulfur-rich setting"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical and redox transformations of reduced carbon and nitrogen species generate cyanide under strongly reducing, UV-driven surface conditions.", "reasoning": "HCN is a canonical prebiotic hub in surface photochemistry and cyanosulfidic networks; while natural sources include atmospheric and geochemical input, local photochemical generation in sulfide-rich settings is consistent with prebiotic cyanide chemistry (Patel et al., 2015; Xu et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Surface Strecker-type synthesis of alanine from pyruvate precursor pool", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "sulfide minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "wet-dry cycling with aminonitrile formation and hydrolysis"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate-derived carbonyl chemistry with ammonia and cyanide forms aminonitrile-type intermediates that hydrolyze to alanine.", "reasoning": "Strecker chemistry is among the best-supported routes to alpha-amino acids in prebiotic environments. Here pyruvate serves as a network-integrating carbonyl source linked to hydrothermal production and surface cyanide chemistry (Miller, 1957; Peltzer et al., 1984; Islam et al., 2003)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite", "greigite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic mineral surfaces in vent pores"}, "mechanism": "Imine formation between pyruvate and ammonia followed by mineral-assisted reduction generates alanine.", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids on mineral surfaces is a plausible hydrothermal route to amino acids, directly connecting keto acid hubs to amino acid pools in iron-sulfur settings (Huber & Wachtershauser, 2003; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Surface HCN oligomerization to adenine", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "concentrating ponds, UV exposure, repeated drying"}, "mechanism": "Oligomerization of HCN through diaminomaleonitrile-like intermediates culminates in purine ring formation.", "reasoning": "HCN oligomerization to adenine is a classic prebiotic route and included here to increase network density around the cyanide hub and connect nitrogen-rich heterocycle chemistry to the same surface feedstock pool (Or\u00f3, 1961; Ferris et al., 1978)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Surface concentration of cyanamide-like nitrogen chemistry to guanidine/urea pool", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_012", "mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals", "TiO2"], "conditions": {"temperature": "310-360K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "dry-heating and rehydration cycles in evaporitic pools"}, "mechanism": "Concentrated nitrile and ammonia chemistry under dehydration/rehydration yields carbamidine and carbamoyl equivalents including guanidine and urea-like products.", "reasoning": "Prebiotic nitrile chemistry can furnish activated nitrogen-rich species such as cyanamide, urea, and related carbamidine donors. Guanidine itself is less directly established than urea/cyanamide, so this node represents a necessary but partly speculative condensation pool feeding downstream guanidination chemistry (Lohrmann & Orgel, 1971; Saladino et al., 2007; speculative extension for arginine assembly)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Biochemical transamination and homologation from glyoxylate/pyruvate/alanine to ornithine pool", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "concentrated prebiotic pools, repeated heating-cooling, mineral interfaces available"}, "mechanism": "Network-level carbonyl homologation and transamination converts alpha-keto acid and amino acid pools into diamino acid products, with ornithine as the emergent C5 diamino acid node.", "reasoning": "Direct prebiotic synthesis of ornithine is not as well established as simple amino acids, but alpha-keto acid/amino acid networks can expand carbon skeleton diversity through aldol-like additions, transamination, and reduction. Ornithine is included as a necessary intermediate for arginine and is therefore a speculative but chemically justified node (Muchowska et al., 2020; Frenkel-Pinter et al., 2021; speculative network-completion step)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Biochemical carbamoylation of ornithine to citrulline", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "condensing pools with dehydration-rehydration cycles"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic attack of ornithine terminal amino group on carbamoyl donor equivalent yields a ureido side chain.", "reasoning": "Citrulline is the immediate carbamoylated precursor to arginine in biology. Prebiotically, urea and related carbamoyl donors can react with amines during drying cycles, making citrulline a plausible intermediate even though direct demonstrations are limited (Lohrmann & Orgel, 1971; Becker et al., 2018; partly speculative connection)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Biochemical guanidination of ornithine to arginine", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "concentrated solute phases, mildly alkaline, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Terminal amino group of ornithine attacks a carbamidine/guanidino donor to form the guanidinium side chain of arginine.", "reasoning": "Guanidination of amines by carbamidine-like donors is chemically plausible and provides the shortest prebiotic route from ornithine to arginine. Direct prebiotic evidence is sparse, so this is a necessary speculative step anchored in known guanidino transfer chemistry and the availability of nitrogen-rich condensation products in cyanide-derived networks (Saladino et al., 2007; Frenkel-Pinter et al., 2021; speculative network-completion step)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Biochemical conversion of citrulline to arginine via guanidino enrichment", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "dehydration-rehydration with concentrated carbamidine donors"}, "mechanism": "Further amidino/guanidino transfer to citrulline-like ureido intermediates yields the fully guanidinated arginine side chain.", "reasoning": "Although less direct than ornithine guanidination, citrulline can be viewed as a chemically proximate intermediate toward arginine under nitrogen-rich condensing conditions. This provides an alternate terminal route and reflects uncertainty in exact prebiotic late-stage chemistry (speculative extension justified by network redundancy and biomimetic analogy)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Direct hydrothermal-to-biochemical ornithine guanidination route", "description": "CO2 reduction builds pyruvate and alanine hydrothermally, feeding a biochemical ornithine node that is guanidinated to arginine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_008", "rxn_011", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_014", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate with surface cyanide alanine route", "description": "Hydrothermal pyruvate is exported to the surface for Strecker-like alanine synthesis, then converted through ornithine to arginine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_011", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_004", "mol_010", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Formate-formaldehyde-glycolaldehyde branch to ornithine", "description": "Hydrothermal C1 fixation produces glycolaldehyde and glyoxylate, which converge with pyruvate/alanine chemistry to form ornithine before guanidination.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_008", "rxn_011", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_005", "mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Surface guanidine pool with hydrothermal alanine input", "description": "Hydrothermal alanine and surface-derived guanidine are combined through the ornithine hub to reach arginine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_008", "rxn_006", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_004", "mol_012", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Citrulline branch from ornithine", "description": "Ornithine is first carbamoylated to citrulline, then further converted to arginine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_008", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_014", "mol_015", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Mixed hydrothermal-surface carbonyl