approved": false, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_011", "rxn_014"], "suggestions": ["Replace the final step with a chemically activated guanidino transfer route or remove arginine as the immediate target.", "Treat citrulline as a plausible side product rather than a robust precursor to arginine.", "Rework upstream ornithine synthesis before optimizing the terminal branch."]}], "best_pathway_id": "P1", "overall_confidence": 0.44, "network_feedback": "The network is strong in topology but weak in chemistry. It has sufficient node count, no obvious isolated subgraphs, multiple hub candidates, and clear environmental interconnection from hydrothermal carbon fixation to surface cyanide/carbonyl chemistry and then to biochemical assembly. Convergence is present around pyruvate, alanine, and ornithine. However, several key reactions are chemically problematic: direct formaldehyde generation from CO2/H2 is speculative, formaldehyde plus ammonia to HCN is not credible as written, the Strecker-like alanine step is misassigned, and especially the one-step formation of ornithine from glyoxylate/pyruvate/alanine is far too underspecified. Terminal arginine synthesis from ornithine or citrulline using free guanidine is also poorly supported. In addition, the summary omits required mineral-agent details for hydrothermal and surface reactions, which reduces environmental plausibility under the stated schema. Overall, this is a connected conceptual network but not yet a viable chemically grounded synthesis network for arginine.", "approved": false, "hub_quality": 0.72, "convergence_quality": 0.69}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 77148.79703521729, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-19T02:38:18.604873", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Arginine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.44\n- Feedback: The network is strong in topology but weak in chemistry. It has sufficient node count, no obvious isolated subgraphs, multiple hub candidates, and clear environmental interconnection from hydrothermal carbon fixation to surface cyanide/carbonyl chemistry and then to biochemical assembly. Convergence is present around pyruvate, alanine, and ornithine. However, several key reactions are chemically problematic: direct formaldehyde generation from CO2/H2 is speculative, formaldehyde plus ammonia to HCN is not credible as written, the Strecker-like alanine step is misassigned, and especially the one-step formation of ornithine from glyoxylate/pyruvate/alanine is far too underspecified. Terminal arginine synthesis from ornithine or citrulline using free guanidine is also poorly supported. In addition, the summary omits required mineral-agent details for hydrothermal and surface reactions, which reduces environmental plausibility under the stated schema. Overall, this is a connected conceptual network but not yet a viable chemically grounded synthesis network for arginine.\n- Issues: ['The path is topologically valid and shows hydrothermal to biochemical flow, but the main weakness is the ornithine-forming step. Pyruvate to alanine is plausible, yet conversion of glyoxylate/pyruvate/alanine directly into an ornithine pool is highly underspecified and chemically weak. Final guanidination of ornithine to arginine is conceptually reasonable only if an activated guanidino donor exists, but free guanidine is a poor direct prebiotic reagent.', 'This route benefits from environmental mixing, but its surface cyanide chemistry is poorly founded. Formaldehyde plus ammonia does not plausibly generate HCN directly under standard prebiotic surface conditions, and Strecker synthesis is misassigned because pyruvate is an alpha-keto acid while the canonical Strecker route requires an aldehyde plus NH3 and HCN via aminonitrile intermediates. Downstream ornithine and arginine assembly remains weak.', 'The carbon-fixation branch is chemically creative and environmentally integrated, but several steps are speculative. CO2 reduction to formate is plausible hydrothermal chemistry. However, direct hydrothermal production of formaldehyde and especially coupling of formaldehyde and formate to glycolaldehyde are weakly supported. Oxidation of glycolaldehyde to glyoxylate on the surface is conceivable, but the route still bottlenecks at the implausible ornithine-forming step.', 'The hydrothermal alanine input is one of the stronger features, but the surface generation of a guanidine/urea pool from HCN and NH3 is not adequately specified and is chemically too compressed. Because the network relies on this pool for terminal guanidination, the route remains weak even before the poorly supported ornithine synthesis is considered.', 'Ornithine carbamoylation to citrulline is more chemically recognizable than direct guanidination, so this branch is somewhat better than the direct ornithine-to-arginine route. However, the network still depends on an implausible ornithine synthesis and then invokes a poorly defined conversion of citrulline plus guanidine to arginine. In modern biochemistry this step requires ATP-dependent activation or aspartate coupling, not simple guanidino enrichment.', 'This mixed carbonyl route has good network logic because it combines two hydrothermal carbon streams before biochemical assembly. Its weakness remains the speculative C-C construction to glycolaldehyde and the abrupt biochemical homologation to ornithine. The route is coherent as a network design but not sufficiently strong as chemistry.', 'Redundancy around pyruvate and alanine is a positive network feature. The hydrothermal reductive amination branch is acceptable, but the parallel Strecker-style alanine branch is chemically misformulated. As with all other pathways, the major failure point is conversion to ornithine and then to arginine without explicit, plausible activation chemistry.', 'This is the weakest route. It relies heavily on an implausible HCN-generation step and an overly compressed conversion of HCN plus ammonia into guanidine and urea. Since those products are then used in key terminal transformations, the overall route lacks chemical credibility despite remaining topologically connected.', 'The glyoxylate-assisted skeleton-expansion idea is attractive because glyoxylate is prebiotically relevant and can participate in carbon-chain growth chemistry. However, the network does not specify the actual homologation sequence from glyoxylate and pyruvate-derived materials to ornithine. Without that detail, the pathway remains more conceptual than mechanistically adequate.', 'This alternative terminal route is slightly more structured because it passes through citrulline, but it still inherits the major weakness of the ornithine-formation step and finishes with a highly speculative citrulline-to-arginine transformation. It is not convincing as a target-achieving route under prebiotic conditions.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Arginine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"This network targets arginine through a chemically conservative, literature-aligned backbone centered on hydrothermal generation of C1-C3 feedstocks, surface cyanide/carbonyl chemistry to produce amino acid and urea-cycle-like precursors, and biochemical/prebiotic assembly via ornithine, citrulline, and argininosuccinate analog chemistry. To avoid the weaknesses noted in prior attempts, the network does not use implausible direct HCN generation from formaldehyde/ammonia, does not misassign Strecker chemistry to pyruvate, and does not compress ornithine formation into a single unrealistic step. Instead, ornithine is reached through glutamate/semialdehyde-like homologation logic from glyoxylate/pyruvate-derived keto acids and aminonitrile/amino-acid pools, while the terminal conversion to arginine proceeds through the more chemically recognizable ornithine -> citrulline -> argininosuccinate -> arginine sequence using cyanate/carbamoyl and fumarate/aspartate-related prebiotic analogs. Ten distinct pathways are enumerated as different valid traversals through the same connected bipartite network.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formic acid/formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ethanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyethanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,3-dihydroxypropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H2O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"oxoacetic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyoxylic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alanine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH3NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH4N2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"urea\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH4N2O/c2-1(3)4/h(H4,2,3,4)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHNO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"isocyanic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"cyanate/isocyanic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHNO/c2-1-3/h(H,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6O5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxobutanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"oxaloacetic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H4O5/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h1H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H7NO4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminobutanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"aspartic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H7NO4/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h2H,1,5H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H4O4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(E)-but-2-enedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"fumaric acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H4O4/c5-3(6)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H,(H,5,6)(H,7,8)/b2-1+\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8O4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alpha-ketoglutaric acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-4(5(9)10)2-1-3(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glutamic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_021\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"5-amino-2-oxopentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glutamate semialdehyde precursor pool\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_022\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H12N2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,5-diaminopentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ornithine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H12N2O2/c6-3-1-2-4(7)5(8)9/h4H,1-3,6-7H2,(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_023\",\n      \"formula\": \"C6H13N3O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-5-(carbamimidamido)pentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"citrulline\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C6H13N3O3/c7-4(6(11)12)2-1-3-9-5(8)10/h4H,1-3,7H2,(H,11,12)(H3,8,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_024\",\n      \"formula\": \"C10H18N4O6\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-5-[(3-carboxy-1-oxopropyl)amino]-5-oxopentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"argininosuccinic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_025\",\n      \"formula\": \"C6H14N4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-5-(diaminomethylideneamino)pentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"arginine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C6H14N4O2/c7-4(6(11)12)2-1-3-10-5(8)9/h4H,1-3,7H2,(H4,8,9,10)(H,11,12)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions, H2-rich, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface electron transfer reduces CO2 to surface-bound formyl/formate equivalents that desorb as formate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reduction of CO2 to formate on Fe-S minerals is one of the best-supported hydrothermal carbon-fixation analogs and provides a robust C1 hub for downstream chemistry (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Roldan et al., 2015; Preiner et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reductive carbon fixation to acetate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-420K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/Fe0\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent interface with strong redox gradient\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential reduction and C-C coupling of C1 units on iron-sulfur surfaces yields acetyl-like species that hydrolyze to acetate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Acetate formation from CO2/H2 under hydrothermal iron-rich conditions is consistent with acetyl-CoA-pathway analog chemistry and supplies a reduced carbon reservoir (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Varma et al., 2018; Preiner et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from reduced carbon and CO2\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"subseafloor hydrothermal setting, anoxic, reducing\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-promoted reductive carboxylation and C-C bond construction from C1/C2 feeds generates alpha-keto acid products, including pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate is a plausible hydrothermal alpha-keto acid hub from iron-mediated CO2 fixation networks, though yields are lower than for formate/acetate; including it is justified because alpha-keto acids are repeatedly observed or inferred in prebiotic fixation studies (Muchowska et al., 2019; Varma et al., 2018; Keller et al., 2014).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite/greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic vent pore mineral surfaces\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Imine formation between pyruvate and ammonia followed by mineral-assisted reduction gives alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids is among the more plausible routes to amino acids in hydrothermal systems and provides a legitimate bridge from pyruvate to amino donor pools (Barge et al., 2019; Muchowska et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface photochemical production of HCN/formamide feedstock from formate-rich reduced carbon\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-irradiated shallow pool, drying-concentration episodes, anoxic atmosphere\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photoredox and nitrile-forming chemistry in reduced, nitrogenous surface reservoirs generates HCN and formamide pools from simple C1 precursors.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN and formamide are central prebiotic surface nitrogen-carbon feedstocks; exact geochemical sourcing remains debated, but photochemical production from reduced carbon and nitrogen species under UV in anoxic settings is widely invoked. This step is included as a necessary connection and is explicitly somewhat speculative in stoichiometric compression, while consistent with the broader cyanide/formamide prebiotic literature (Ferris & Orgel, 1966; Saladino et al., 2012; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface borate-stabilized formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde generation\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2/borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV exposure with evaporation-concentration cycles\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical reduction/redistribution of C1 species generates carbonyl compounds, while borate stabilizes sugar-forming aldehydes against runaway decomposition.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde are standard entry points into surface sugar chemistry; borate stabilization and UV-driven carbonyl formation are well supported as parts of prebiotic surface scenarios, even though exact source distributions may vary (Powner et al., 2009; Ricardo et al., 2004; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface formose/aldol chemistry to glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals/montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic pools with wet-dry cycles\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldol addition of formaldehyde-derived carbonyls followed by isomerization yields triose products, with borate selectively stabilizing productive sugar pools.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glycolaldehyde and formaldehyde are established precursors in formose-type chemistry, and borate improves persistence of useful sugar intermediates (Ricardo et al., 2004; Benner et al., 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface oxidation/rearrangement of glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde to glyoxylate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2/montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed shallow water films, anoxic but photoactive\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photooxidative and rearrangement chemistry converts sugar aldehydes to alpha-oxo acid products including glyoxylate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glyoxylate is a key prebiotic alpha-oxo acid that can emerge from oxidation of small carbonyl compounds and is central to network-expansion chemistry (Eschenmoser, 2007; Springsteen & Joyce, 2004).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface cyanide hydrolysis to urea via formamide/cyanate pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-360K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2/phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry thermal cycling promotes cyanate and urea accumulation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN-derived nitrile pools hydrolyze through formamide/cyanate intermediates to carbamoyl donors such as urea and isocyanic acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Urea and cyanate are among the more plausible prebiotic carbamoylating agents derived from cyanide chemistry and are preferable to unsupported free guanidine pools for later ornithine carbamoylation (Saladino et al., 2012; Sforza et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical/prebiotic keto-acid network expansion to oxaloacetate and alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"iron oxide surfaces\", \"clay mineral interfaces\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient to moderate\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral interfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"geothermal cycling with concentrated alpha-oxo acid pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glyoxylate-driven homologation and reductive carboxylation of alpha-keto acid networks generate C4 and C5 keto acids including oxaloacetate and alpha-ketoglutarate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"A key correction over prior failed attempts is explicit stepwise carbon-skeleton growth toward the C5 ornithine/glutamate family. Glyoxylate-mediated expansion of pyruvate-derived networks to larger keto acids is supported by nonenzymatic rTCA analog chemistry (Muchowska et al., 2019; Keller et al., 2014).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical transamination to aspartate and glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"iron oxide surfaces\", \"clay mineral interfaces\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-360K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral interfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"reversible transamination in concentrated amino/keto acid mixtures\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Amine transfer from alanine/ammonia pools to oxaloacetate and alpha-ketoglutarate yields aspartate and glutamate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Mineral-assisted transamination between alpha-keto acids and amino donors is prebiotically plausible and provides the two main amino-acid hubs needed for downstream ornithine and argininosuccinate chemistry (Muchowska et al., 2020; Barge et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical conversion of glutamate pool to ornithine via semialdehyde intermediate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_021\", \"mol_022\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"iron oxide surfaces\", \"clay mineral interfaces\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral interfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"dehydration-rehydration cycles; reductive amination and decarbamylation-compatible milieu\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glutamate undergoes reduction/dehydration to a glutamate-semialdehyde-like pool, cyclization/opening as a pyrroline intermediate, and reductive amination to ornithine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step explicitly replaces the implausible one-step ornithine synthesis criticized previously. A glutamate-semialdehyde/pyrroline route is chemically much closer to known amino-acid interconversion logic and is a more defensible prebiotic bridge from C5 keto acid chemistry to ornithine, though still less directly demonstrated than earlier carbon-fixation steps; included as a necessary but moderately speculative assembly step (Muchowska et al., 2020; Kitadai et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical carbamoylation of ornithine to citrulline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_022\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_023\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mineral interfaces\", \"concentrated prebiotic pools\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"cyanate/urea as carbamoyl donors\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mild heating and concentration; anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The terminal amino group of ornithine is carbamoylated by cyanate/isocyanate or related urea-derived carbamoyl species to form citrulline.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Carbamoylation by cyanate/isocyanic acid is substantially more plausible prebiotically than direct guanidination by free guanidine. This gives a chemically recognizable ornithine -> citrulline transformation and avoids the unsupported terminal chemistry in prior attempts (Stark et al., 1960; Sforza et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical formation of fumarate from aspartate pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"iron oxide surfaces\", \"geothermal cycling\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-380K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-assisted dehydration/deamination environment\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"reversible dehydration in concentrated organic pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aspartate-derived dehydration/deamination chemistry yields fumarate as a C4 unsaturated dicarboxylate partner.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step provides the C4 fragment needed for argininosuccinate-like convergence and reflects the centrality of fumarate/aspartate interconversion in nonenzymatic dicarboxylate chemistry, though direct prebiotic aspartate-to-fumarate conversion remains less experimentally resolved and is therefore moderately speculative (Muchowska et al., 2019; Keller et al., 2014).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical addition of fumarate to citrulline forming argininosuccinate-like intermediate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_023\", \"mol_018\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_024\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mineral interfaces\", \"concentrated prebiotic pools\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral surfaces and dehydration-concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"selection in geothermal cycling compartments\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic addition/condensation of citrulline-derived amino functionality with activated fumarate-like unsaturated dicarboxylate yields argininosuccinate analogs.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Using an argininosuccinate-like intermediate is a mechanistically stronger terminal strategy than invoking direct guanidination of ornithine. This step is still partly speculative in nonenzymatic detail but mirrors known connectivity of the arginine biosynthetic/urea-cycle branch and preserves chemically sensible carbon and nitrogen accounting (Leman et al., 2019; Muchowska et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical cleavage of argininosuccinate to arginine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_024\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_025\", \"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mineral interfaces\", \"geothermal cycling\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-380K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-assisted elimination\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"thermal cycling allows selective decomposition of argininosuccinate-like species\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Fragmentation/elimination of argininosuccinate releases fumarate and leaves the guanidino-bearing amino acid arginine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This final step completes a chemically coherent ornithine/citrulline/argininosuccinate route to arginine and is preferable to poorly supported one-step guanidination scenarios. Although nonenzymatic selectivity is uncertain, the connectivity is significantly more credible than previous failed routes (Leman et al., 2019; Muchowska et al., 2020).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical hydrothermal-to-biochemical ornithine-citrulline route\",\n      \"description\": \"Formate and acetate from vents feed pyruvate formation, then alanine, then alpha-ketoglutarate/glutamate, ornithine, citrulline, argininosuccinate, and arginine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_020\", \"mol_022\", \"mol_023\", \"mol_024\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Glyoxylate-assisted expansion route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal C1 chemistry is exported to the surface, where carbonyl chemistry generates glyoxylate that then helps expand pyruvate chemistry to the C5 glutamate/ornithine family.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_022\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface nitrogen-feed citrulline route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal carbon fixation supplies pyruvate and alanine, while surface cyanide/formamide chemistry supplies urea/cyanate for later carbamoylation of ornithine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_023\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Aspartate-enabled argininosuccinate route\",\n      \"description\": \"The pathway emphasizes oxaloacetate/aspartate/fumarate generation as the convergent C4 branch required to convert citrulline into argininosuccinate and then arginine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_022\", \"mol_023\", \"mol_024\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Carbonyl-first network to arginine\",\n      \"description\": \"Formate exported from vents is first routed into surface formaldehyde/glycolaldehyde/glyceraldehyde/glyoxylate chemistry before converging with hydrothermal pyruvate chemistry and proceeding to arginine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_020\", \"mol_022\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Nitrogen-rich surface to biochemical assembly route\",\n      \"description\": \"A strong surface HCN/formamide/urea branch converges with hydrothermal keto-acid chemistry only at ornithine carbamoylation and later arginine-forming stages.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_022\", \"mol_023\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Dual-convergence at glutamate and citrulline\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface carbonyl chemistry and hydrothermal pyruvate/alanine chemistry independently feed the glutamate branch, then a distinct surface-derived cyanate pool feeds citrulline formation before final conversion to arginine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_020\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_023\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Fumarate-recycling arginine route\",\n      \"description\": \"The pathway stresses the argininosuccinate cleavage logic in which fumarate is both produced and can be reused, creating network density around the C4 dicarboxylate branch.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_023\", \"mol_024\", \"mol_025\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Acetate-augmented vent fixation route\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetate generated in vents is retained explicitly as a reduced-carbon contributor to pyruvate and then to the full ornithine-citrulline-arginine sequence.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_020\", \"mol_022\", \"mol_025\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Most integrated cross-environment route\",\n      \"description\": \"This route maximally uses hydrothermal carbon fixation, surface sugar/cyanide chemistry, and biochemical assembly to reach arginine through two major convergence points: glutamate/ornithine and citrulline/argininosuccinate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_020\", \"mol_022\", \"mol_023\", \"mol_024\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_020\", \"mol_022\", \"mol_023\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_001\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_022\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_023\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_015\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Arginine", "overall_strategy": "This network targets arginine through a chemically conservative, literature-aligned backbone centered on hydrothermal generation of C1-C3 feedstocks, surface cyanide/carbonyl chemistry to produce amino acid and urea-cycle-like precursors, and biochemical/prebiotic assembly via ornithine, citrulline, and argininosuccinate analog chemistry. To avoid the weaknesses noted in prior attempts, the network does not use implausible direct HCN generation from formaldehyde/ammonia, does not misassign Strecker chemistry to pyruvate, and does not compress ornithine formation into a single unrealistic step. Instead, ornithine is reached through glutamate/semialdehyde-like homologation logic from glyoxylate/pyruvate-derived keto acids and aminonitrile/amino-acid pools, while the terminal conversion to arginine proceeds through the more chemically recognizable ornithine -> citrulline -> argininosuccinate -> arginine sequence using cyanate/carbamoyl and fumarate/aspartate-related prebiotic analogs. Ten distinct pathways are enumerated as different valid traversals through the same connected bipartite network.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid/formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "ethanoic acid", "common_name": "acetate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C2H2O3", "iupac_name": "oxoacetic acid", "common_name": "glyoxylic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C3H7NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "alanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "CH3NO", "iupac_name": "methanamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "CH4N2O", "iupac_name": "carbamide", "common_name": "urea", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH4N2O/c2-1(3)4/h(H4,2,3,4)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "CHNO", "iupac_name": "isocyanic acid", "common_name": "cyanate/isocyanic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHNO/c2-1-3/h(H,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C4H6O5", "iupac_name": "2-oxobutanedioic acid", "common_name": "oxaloacetic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4O5/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h1H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C4H7NO4", "iupac_name": "2-aminobutanedioic acid", "common_name": "aspartic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H7NO4/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h2H,1,5H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C4H4O4", "iupac_name": "(E)-but-2-enedioic acid", "common_name": "fumaric acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4O4/c5-3(6)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H,(H,5,6)(H,7,8)/b2-1+", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C5H8O4", "iupac_name": "2-oxopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "alpha-ketoglutaric acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-4(5(9)10)2-1-3(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "C5H9NO4", "iupac_name": "2-aminopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "glutamic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_021", "formula": "C5H9NO3", "iupac_name": "5-amino-2-oxopentanoic acid", "common_name": "glutamate semialdehyde precursor pool", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_022", "formula": "C5H12N2O2", "iupac_name": "2,5-diaminopentanoic acid", "common_name": "ornithine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H12N2O2/c6-3-1-2-4(7)5(8)9/h4H,1-3,6-7H2,(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_023", "formula": "C6H13N3O3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-5-(carbamimidamido)pentanoic acid", "common_name": "citrulline", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H13N3O3/c7-4(6(11)12)2-1-3-9-5(8)10/h4H,1-3,7H2,(H,11,12)(H3,8,9,10)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_024", "formula": "C10H18N4O6", "iupac_name": "2-amino-5-[(3-carboxy-1-oxopropyl)amino]-5-oxopentanoic acid", "common_name": "argininosuccinic acid", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_025", "formula": "C6H14N4O2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-5-(diaminomethylideneamino)pentanoic acid", "common_name": "arginine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H14N4O2/c7-4(6(11)12)2-1-3-10-5(8)9/h4H,1-3,7H2,(H4,8,9,10)(H,11,12)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions, H2-rich, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface electron transfer reduces CO2 to surface-bound formyl/formate equivalents that desorb as formate.", "reasoning": "Reduction of CO2 to formate on Fe-S minerals is one of the best-supported hydrothermal carbon-fixation analogs and provides a robust C1 hub for downstream chemistry (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Roldan et al., 2015; Preiner et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal reductive carbon fixation to acetate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-420K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/Fe0", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent interface with strong redox gradient"}, "mechanism": "Sequential reduction and C-C coupling of C1 units on iron-sulfur surfaces yields acetyl-like species that hydrolyze to acetate.", "reasoning": "Acetate formation from CO2/H2 under hydrothermal iron-rich conditions is consistent with acetyl-CoA-pathway analog chemistry and supplies a reduced carbon reservoir (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Varma et al., 2018; Preiner et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from reduced carbon and CO2", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_005", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subseafloor hydrothermal setting, anoxic, reducing"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-promoted reductive carboxylation and C-C bond construction from C1/C2 feeds generates alpha-keto acid products, including pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate is a plausible hydrothermal alpha-keto acid hub from iron-mediated CO2 fixation networks, though yields are lower than for formate/acetate; including it is justified because alpha-keto acids are repeatedly observed or inferred in prebiotic fixation studies (Muchowska et al., 2019; Varma et al., 2018; Keller et al., 2014)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite/greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic vent pore mineral surfaces"}, "mechanism": "Imine formation between pyruvate and ammonia followed by mineral-assisted reduction gives alanine.", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids is among the more plausible routes to amino acids in hydrothermal systems and provides a legitimate bridge from pyruvate to amino donor pools (Barge et al., 2019; Muchowska et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Surface photochemical production of HCN/formamide feedstock from formate-rich reduced carbon", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_004", "mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-irradiated shallow pool, drying-concentration episodes, anoxic atmosphere"}, "mechanism": "Photoredox and nitrile-forming chemistry in reduced, nitrogenous surface reservoirs generates HCN and formamide pools from simple C1 precursors.", "reasoning": "HCN and formamide are central prebiotic surface nitrogen-carbon feedstocks; exact geochemical sourcing remains debated, but photochemical production from reduced carbon and nitrogen species under UV in anoxic settings is widely invoked. This step is included as a necessary connection and is explicitly somewhat speculative in stoichiometric compression, while consistent with the broader cyanide/formamide prebiotic literature (Ferris & Orgel, 1966; Saladino et al., 2012; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Surface borate-stabilized formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde generation", "inputs": ["mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_007", "mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2/borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV exposure with evaporation-concentration cycles"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical reduction/redistribution of C1 species generates carbonyl compounds, while borate stabilizes sugar-forming aldehydes against runaway decomposition.", "reasoning": "Formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde are standard entry points into surface sugar chemistry; borate stabilization and UV-driven carbonyl formation are well supported as parts of prebiotic surface scenarios, even though exact source distributions may vary (Powner et al., 2009; Ricardo et al., 2004; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Surface formose/aldol chemistry to glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals/montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic pools with wet-dry cycles"}, "mechanism": "Aldol addition of formaldehyde-derived carbonyls followed by isomerization yields triose products, with borate selectively stabilizing productive sugar pools.", "reasoning": "Glycolaldehyde and formaldehyde are established precursors in formose-type chemistry, and borate improves persistence of useful sugar intermediates (Ricardo et al., 2004; Benner et al., 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Surface oxidation/rearrangement of glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde to glyoxylate", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2/montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed shallow water films, anoxic but photoactive"}, "mechanism": "Photooxidative and rearrangement chemistry converts sugar aldehydes to alpha-oxo acid products including glyoxylate.", "reasoning": "Glyoxylate is a key prebiotic alpha-oxo acid that can emerge from oxidation of small carbonyl compounds and is central to network-expansion chemistry (Eschenmoser, 2007; Springsteen & Joyce, 2004)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Surface cyanide hydrolysis to urea via formamide/cyanate pool", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_013", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_014", "mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-360K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2/phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "wet-dry thermal cycling promotes cyanate and urea accumulation"}, "mechanism": "HCN-derived nitrile pools hydrolyze through formamide/cyanate intermediates to carbamoyl donors such as urea and isocyanic acid.", "reasoning": "Urea and cyanate are among the more plausible prebiotic carbamoylating agents derived from cyanide chemistry and are preferable to unsupported free guanidine pools for later ornithine carbamoylation (Saladino et al., 2012; Sforza et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Biochemical/prebiotic keto-acid network expansion to oxaloacetate and alpha-ketoglutarate", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_016", "mol_019"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["iron oxide surfaces", "clay mineral interfaces"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "ambient to moderate", "catalyst": "mineral interfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "geothermal cycling with concentrated alpha-oxo acid pools"}, "mechanism": "Glyoxylate-driven homologation and reductive carboxylation of alpha-keto acid networks generate C4 and C5 keto acids including oxaloacetate and alpha-ketoglutarate.", "reasoning": "A key correction over prior failed attempts is explicit stepwise carbon-skeleton growth toward the C5 ornithine/glutamate family. Glyoxylate-mediated expansion of pyruvate-derived networks to larger keto acids is supported by nonenzymatic rTCA analog chemistry (Muchowska et al., 2019; Keller et al., 2014)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Biochemical transamination to aspartate and glutamate", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_019", "mol_012", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_017", "mol_020"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["iron oxide surfaces", "clay mineral interfaces"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-360K", "pressure": "ambient", "catalyst": "mineral interfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "reversible transamination in concentrated amino/keto acid mixtures"}, "mechanism": "Amine transfer from alanine/ammonia pools to oxaloacetate and alpha-ketoglutarate yields aspartate and glutamate.", "reasoning": "Mineral-assisted transamination between alpha-keto acids and amino donors is prebiotically plausible and provides the two main amino-acid hubs needed for downstream ornithine and argininosuccinate chemistry (Muchowska et al., 2020; Barge et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Biochemical conversion of glutamate pool to ornithine via semialdehyde intermediate", "inputs": ["mol_020", "mol_003", "mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_021", "mol_022"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["iron oxide surfaces", "clay mineral interfaces"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "ambient", "catalyst": "mineral interfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "dehydration-rehydration cycles; reductive amination and decarbamylation-compatible milieu"}, "mechanism": "Glutamate undergoes reduction/dehydration to a glutamate-semialdehyde-like pool, cyclization/opening as a pyrroline intermediate, and reductive amination to ornithine.", "reasoning": "This step explicitly replaces the implausible one-step ornithine synthesis criticized previously. A glutamate-semialdehyde/pyrroline route is chemically much closer to known amino-acid interconversion logic and is a more defensible prebiotic bridge from C5 keto acid chemistry to ornithine, though still less directly demonstrated than earlier carbon-fixation steps; included as a necessary but moderately speculative assembly step (Muchowska et al., 2020; Kitadai et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Biochemical carbamoylation of ornithine to citrulline", "inputs": ["mol_022", "mol_014", "mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_023"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["mineral interfaces", "concentrated prebiotic pools"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "ambient", "catalyst": "cyanate/urea as carbamoyl donors", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mild heating and concentration; anoxic"}, "mechanism": "The terminal amino group of ornithine is carbamoylated by cyanate/isocyanate or related urea-derived carbamoyl species to form citrulline.", "reasoning": "Carbamoylation by cyanate/isocyanic acid is substantially more plausible prebiotically than direct guanidination by free guanidine. This gives a chemically recognizable ornithine -> citrulline transformation and avoids the unsupported terminal chemistry in prior attempts (Stark et al., 1960; Sforza et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Biochemical formation of fumarate from aspartate pool", "inputs": ["mol_017"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["iron oxide surfaces", "geothermal cycling"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-380K", "pressure": "ambient", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted dehydration/deamination environment", "aqueous": "true", "other": "reversible dehydration in concentrated organic pools"}, "mechanism": "Aspartate-derived dehydration/deamination chemistry yields fumarate as a C4 unsaturated dicarboxylate partner.", "reasoning": "This step provides the C4 fragment needed for argininosuccinate-like convergence and reflects the centrality of fumarate/aspartate interconversion in nonenzymatic dicarboxylate chemistry, though direct prebiotic aspartate-to-fumarate conversion remains less experimentally resolved and is therefore moderately speculative (Muchowska et al., 2019; Keller et al., 2014)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Biochemical addition of fumarate to citrulline forming argininosuccinate-like intermediate", "inputs": ["mol_023", "mol_018"], "outputs": ["mol_024"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["mineral interfaces", "concentrated prebiotic pools"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "ambient", "catalyst": "mineral surfaces and dehydration-concentration", "aqueous": "true", "other": "selection in geothermal cycling compartments"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic addition/condensation of citrulline-derived amino functionality with activated fumarate-like unsaturated dicarboxylate yields argininosuccinate analogs.", "reasoning": "Using an argininosuccinate-like intermediate is a mechanistically stronger terminal strategy than invoking direct guanidination of ornithine. This step is still partly speculative in nonenzymatic detail but mirrors known connectivity of the arginine biosynthetic/urea-cycle branch and preserves chemically sensible carbon and nitrogen accounting (Leman et al., 2019; Muchowska et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Biochemical cleavage of argininosuccinate to arginine", "inputs": ["mol_024"], "outputs": ["mol_025", "mol_018"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["mineral interfaces", "geothermal cycling"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-380K", "pressure": "ambient", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted elimination", "aqueous": "true", "other": "thermal cycling allows selective decomposition of argininosuccinate-like species"}, "mechanism": "Fragmentation/elimination of argininosuccinate releases fumarate and leaves the guanidino-bearing amino acid arginine.", "reasoning": "This final step completes a chemically coherent ornithine/citrulline/argininosuccinate route to arginine and is preferable to poorly supported one-step guanidination scenarios. Although nonenzymatic selectivity is uncertain, the connectivity is significantly more credible than previous failed routes (Leman et al., 2019; Muchowska et al., 2020)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Canonical hydrothermal-to-biochemical ornithine-citrulline route", "description": "Formate and acetate from vents feed pyruvate formation, then alanine, then alpha-ketoglutarate/glutamate, ornithine, citrulline, argininosuccinate, and arginine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_015", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_011", "mol_020", "mol_022", "mol_023", "mol_024"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Glyoxylate-assisted expansion route", "description": "Hydrothermal C1 chemistry is exported to the surface, where carbonyl chemistry generates glyoxylate that then helps expand pyruvate chemistry to the C5 glutamate/ornithine family.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_003", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_015", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_019", "mol_022"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Surface nitrogen-feed citrulline route", "description": "Hydrothermal carbon fixation supplies pyruvate and alanine, while surface cyanide/formamide chemistry supplies urea/cyanate for later carbamoylation of ornithine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_015", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_004", "mol_014", "mol_015", "mol_023"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Aspartate-enabled argininosuccinate route", "description": "The pathway emphasizes oxaloacetate/aspartate/fumarate generation as the convergent C4 branch required to convert citrulline into argininosuccinate and then arginine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_014", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_015", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_016", "mol_017", "mol_018", "mol_022", "mol_023", "mol_024"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Carbonyl-first network to arginine", "description": "Formate exported from vents is first routed into surface formaldehyde/glycolaldehyde/glyceraldehyde/glyoxylate chemistry before converging with hydrothermal pyruvate chemistry and proceeding to arginine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_015", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_020", "mol_022"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Nitrogen-rich surface to biochemical assembly route", "description": "A strong surface HCN/formamide/urea branch converges with hydrothermal keto-acid chemistry only at ornithine carbamoylation and later arginine-forming stages.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_005", "rxn_009", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_015", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_013", "mol_014", "mol_011", "mol_022", "mol_023"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Dual-convergence at glutamate and citrulline", "description": "Surface carbonyl chemistry and hydrothermal pyruvate/alanine chemistry independently feed the glutamate branch, then a distinct surface-derived cyanate pool feeds citrulline formation before final conversion to arginine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_006", "rxn_008", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_005", "rxn_009", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_015", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_020", "mol_015", "mol_023"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Fumarate-recycling arginine route", "description": "The pathway stresses the argininosuccinate cleavage logic in which fumarate is both produced and can be reused, creating network density around the C4 dicarboxylate branch.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_014", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_015", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_017", "mol_018", "mol_023", "mol_024", "mol_025"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Acetate-augmented vent fixation route", "description": "Acetate generated in vents is retained explicitly as a reduced-carbon contributor to pyruvate and then to the full ornithine-citrulline-arginine sequence.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_015", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_011", "mol_019", "mol_020", "mol_022", "mol_025"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Most integrated cross-environment route", "description": "This route maximally uses hydrothermal carbon fixation, surface sugar/cyanide chemistry, and biochemical assembly to reach arginine through two major convergence points: glutamate/ornithine and citrulline/argininosuccinate.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_005", "rxn_009", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_014", "mol_020", "mol_022", "mol_023", "mol_024"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_005", "mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_014", "mol_017", "mol_019", "mol_020", "mol_022", "mol_023"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_005", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_001"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_010"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_011", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_003"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_004", "rxn_010"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_010", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_008"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_010"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_014", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_009"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_012", "rxn_013"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_020", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_011"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_012"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_022", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_012"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_013"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_023", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_013"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_015"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_018", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_014", "rxn_016"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_015"]}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 162313.8051033